\begin_layout Section*
Abstract
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define a minimal machine that operates on relations rather than substances.
 It consists of a directed relation 
\begin_inset Formula $A\rightarrow B$
\end_inset

 and a third position 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 that acts on the relation.
 The third position (the parasite) can operate either as noise or as a metastable entity.
 Roles 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,B,C)$
\end_inset

 are not intrinsic and may permute suddenly and without warning.
 A distance parameter controls the strength of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

's action.
 We show how this machine generates structure without conserved quantities or predefined ontology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The condition for role permutation remains unspecified.
 The signatory of the concept (Michel Serres) does gives us suddenness,
 circularity,
 feedback,
 sequence,
 and interruption,
 but no clear variable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
1.
 Primitive structure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with a directed relation:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\rightarrow B
\]

\end_inset

and a third position 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 that acts on the relation:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C\triangleright(A\rightarrow B).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Note:
 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B,C$
\end_inset

 are positions within a relational configuration.
 We will have more to say about the positions (also referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

stations
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

).
 It will suffice for now to note that these positions are not occupied by substances but by metastable configurations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
2.
 Distance and coupling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $d\ge0$
\end_inset

 denote the distance of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 to the relation.
 Define coupling:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k=\frac{1}{d+\epsilon}.
\]

\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $d\to\infty$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $k\to0$
\end_inset

 (negligible influence).
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $d\to0$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $k\to\infty$
\end_inset

 (dominant influence).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
3.
 Noise and metastability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third position 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 operates in two regimes:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Argument 1
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
leftmargin=2em
\end_layout

\end_inset


\series bold
Noise
\series default
:
 perturbative,
 destabilizing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Metastability
\series default
:
 stabilized,
 structuring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These are not distinct ontologies but regimes of the same position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
4.
 Transformation of relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R(A,B)$
\end_inset

 denote the baseline relation strength.
 Define a transformation:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R'(A,B)=T(R(A,B),C,k).
\]

\end_inset

Two cases:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{Noise: } & R'=R+\eta(C)\,k\\
\text{Metastability: } & R'=R+\alpha\,C\,k
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is a stochastic perturbation and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 a scaling constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
5.
 Role permutation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Positions are not fixed.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 be a permutation:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A,B,C)\mapsto\sigma(A,B,C).
\]

\end_inset

This encodes sudden reassignment of roles.
\end_layout

